 no need for landing future missions in different locations, easing the build-up of a base.<br>
<br>
If used to return to the TEI ship, the same hopper can be reused as the reentry vehicle for the next crew. I would suggest sending one over early and have the crew land in the second. If the crew lands far from the habitat, the lander can easily be hopped over. The crew would leave in one and take it back to Earth, or it could be left in Mars orbit. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1441<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/12/02 10:14:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=184.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: RTG Rovers</span><hr size=1> I don't know just how safe flying from point to point on the planet<br>
