Allow me to indeed correct you: <br>
As I had suspected, the RTGS need intenssive shielding ( several layers) to protect other components/subsystems of the spacecraft from both the high temperatures released by the radiactive decay processes as well as from the radiation itself. (Please read from the Safety Issues part of your suggestd web site..all this is well explained there). <br>
Thus apparently a use in manned operated rovers would not be very well suited unless effective shielding could be provided.. my guess is that this shielding would make the rover quite heavy and thus highly innefficient for the purpose of taking humans around the surface of a planet specially when targeted at the polar regions as it was my original point. The shielding to protect the tripulation as well as to avoid the heat being transfered to the underliying ice would make it a non suitable transportation system in my view. <br>
Of course my point is only vaild if we are considering current shielding materials.. not new yet-to-be-found alloys which could be very thin while remaining highly effective. An improovement would also take place if we had a highly conductive material able to convert most of the heat released direclty into electricity..<br>
As a foot note, the RTGs are as well quite low in their thermal energy to electricity conversion, since only about 10-11% of the heat generated by spontaneaous fission decays is converted into electricity (I have adopted the theoretical term of &quot;spontaneaous fission decay&quot; for radiactivity, since I find it more correct). Thus, one can imagine how much heat is released by simply noticing that the rest of the 90% of it is not converted into electricity. In fact, in Space propulsion applications, the RTGs release their residual heat directly onto the sorrounding space environment  however taking precautions towards the protection of the other spacecraft subsystems by radiating that heat at a distance from the spacecraft. Same sketch should/would apply to a rover... evermore since a human supposedly would be on it, thus one would need a radiating surface extending out at a prudential distance from the rover in order to get rid of that 90% residual heat.<br>
